# Group Library Endpoints
![alt text](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SMARTRACTECHNOLOGY/smartcosmos-objects-api/master/images/endpoints/Endpoint_Library-Label.png "Library Endpoint")

## DRAFT

This component is not yet in the production release of SMART COSMOS Objects.

## Overview

SMART COSMOS Objects allows you to impose a hierarchy on your stored objects
(which includes users, devices, files, metadata, etc.) by linking them to
library elements, and linking library elements to each other. In the example
below (which matches the example in the initial version of the Objects
configuration file, objects.yml, and may be everything you need), a Shelf
can only be the child of a Library, a Book can only be the child of a Shelf,
and so on. Library elements do not have to have parents, i.e., a Shelf can
have Books and those Books can have Chapters and so on, without the Shelf
having to have a parent Library. However, the Shelf can have at most one
parent Library (a Library can of course have an arbitrary number of Shelves),
and so on down the hierarchy. You can have as many Libraries as you want,
and move Shelves from one to another, and similarly for the rest of the hierarchy.

The highest level element in the hierarchy (Library, in this example)
cannot have a parent. The lowest level element in the hierarchy (PageEntry,
in this example) cannot have children. There are no restrictions on the
number of levels in the hierarcy, but every level must have a distinct name.
Think your hierarchy through carefully in advance of starting to use it;
reorganizing your data from one hierarchy schema to another will in most
cases be non-trivial and best done in collaboration with a SMARTRAC
support engineer.

The "Link Flags" element in objects.yml declares which kinds of library elements
can have objects (again, to include users, devices, files, metadata, etc.) linked
to them. In this example, the "normal" case holds, in which objects can only be
linked to the lowest level of the hierarchy tree, i.e., PageEntry. If you wanted
to allow objects to be linked also to a Shelf, you would change the second-to-last
entry to "true", and if you wanted to allow objects to be attached to library
elements at eny level of the tree, you would change them all to "true".

A library link is implemented with the normal SMART COSMOS Relationship, and
using the normal Relationship REST endpoints. The only additional constraint
in play is this: if the entityReferenceType in the relationship is a LibraryElement,
the Type field of the relationship will be set immutably to LibraryLink.

Note that as with any relationship in SMART COSMOS, deleting a relationship (i.e.,
a library link) has no effect on either the library element or the linked object.
  
## Library Fields
Field | Data Type | Required | Can Update | Serialization Level | Default Value
----- | --------- | -------- | ---------- | ------------------- | -------------
urn | UUID  | true | false | Minimum | Generated
account | IAccount  | true | false | Full | Generated
lastModifiedTimestamp | long   | true | false | Standard | Generated
name | String | true | true | Standard | none
moniker | String  | false | true | Full | null
description | String  | false | true | Standard | null 
activeFlag | Boolean  | true | true | Standard  | true
libraryElementType | one of "Library", "Shelf", ... (see "Library Hierarchy" below) | true | false | Standard | defaultLibrary, defaultShelf... 
parent | see "Library Hierarchy" below | false | true | Standard | null

### Field Notes
- The `libraryElementType` field defines the position of the library element in the hierarchy of library elements, and thus constrains its
attachments to its parent and children. A (for example) shelf is not required to have a parent, and will be created without one if an already
existing parent is not specified at creation time. In this case the shelf can later be attached to any already existing library.
- The `parent` field defines this element's attachment in the library hierarchy. Every library element (except for libraryElementType library)
can have a parent of the appropriate library element type, if it has a parent at all.
- An object which is not a library element can only be attached to a Page Entry element. The relatedEntityReferenceType, RelatedReferenceUrn
and deleteFromLibrary fields must be unset for every library element which is not a Page Entry.
- The `name` field is required, and must be HTML-compliant (i.e., no special characters, no space characters...). Unique naming in a library hierarchy is enforced: a shelf cannot have two books with the same name, for example.
  On the other hand, two books with the same name can be attached to two distinct shelves, not that we would recommend this.

### The Default Library Hierarchy

Name | Type | Parent Type | Children Type
-----| ---- | ----------- | -------------
Library | Library | none | Shelf
Shelf | Shelf | Library | Book
Book | Book | Shelf | Chapter
Chapter | Chapter | Book | ChapterSection
Chapter Section | ChapterSection | Chapter | Page
Page | Page | ChapterSection | PageEntry
Page Entry | PageEntry | Page | none

## Linking Objects to Library Elements

To link an Object (or User, File, Metadata, Device, Geospatial, and so on) to a Library Element, use the Relationship
endpoints, with the following caveats:

Unless you have specified in your server configuration that a particular LibraryElementType (PageEntry, in all of the examples
here) can accept links, attempts to create a relationship the Object (relatedEntityReference) to the Library Element (EntityReference) will be rejected.

When the entityReferenceType of a relationship is "LibraryElement", the Type field of the Relationship itself will be set immutably
to LibraryLink.

There is a detailed discussion of Library functionality in objects.yml, the server's configuration file. Please read that
section carefully and discuss any questions with your SMARTRAC support engineer before implementing a Library hierarchy.


## Library Management [/rest/library]
### Create a new library element [PUT]

The following library fields may be used to create a new record:

- `moniker` is optional and constrained to 2048 characters may be omitted; defaults to **null**
- `description` is optional and constrained to 1024 characters and may be omitted; defaults to **null**
